05349nam a22007335i 9780271093017DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710930177 a10.1515/97802710930172doi  a(DE-B1597)623989  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aN5961b.I26 2022 7aART0150702bisacsh04a709.0222300aIconography Beyond the Crossroads :bImage, Meaning, and Method in Medieval Art /ced. by Pamela A. Patton, Catherine A. Fernandez. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b37 color/46 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSigna: Papers of the Index of Medieval Art at Princeton University ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction: Beyond the Crossroads: Iconography and Its Evo -- t1 Iconography and Iconology at Princeton -- t2 Whose Iconography? -- t3 Iconology After the Spatial Turn -- t4 Iconographies of Progress -- t5 The Iconography of Healing and Damaged Bodies in the Menil Collection and the Kariye Camii: Methodological Reflections -- t6 Pictured in Relief: Comparative Iconology and Civilizational Time Zones at Monreale and Quanzhou, ca. 1186–ca. 1238 -- t7 Iconography Deconstructed, from Mâle to the Alt Right -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume assesses how current approaches to iconology and iconography break new ground in understanding the signification and reception of medieval images, both in their own time and in the modern world.Framed by critical essays that apply explicitly historiographical and sociopolitical perspectives to key moments in the evolution of the field, the volume’s case studies focus on how iconographic meaning is shaped by factors such as medieval modes of dialectical thought, the problem of representing time, the movement of the viewer in space, the fragmentation and injury of both image and subject, and the complex strategy of comparing distant cultural paradigms. The contributions are linked by a commitment to understanding how medieval images made meaning; to highlighting the heuristic value of new perspectives and methods in exploring the work of the image in both the Middle Ages and our own time; and to recognizing how subtle entanglements between scholarship and society can provoke mutual and unexpected transformations in both. Collectively, the essays demonstrate the expansiveness, flexibility, and dynamism of iconographic studies as a scholarly field that is still heartily engaged in the challenge of its own remaking.Along with the volume editors, the contributors include Madeline H. Caviness, Beatrice Kitzinger, Aden Kumler, Christopher R. Lakey, Glenn Peers, Jennifer Purtle, and Elizabeth Sears.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aArt, MedievalvCongresses. 0aChristian art and symbolismyMedieval, 500-1500vCongresses. 7aART / History / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aCaviness, Madeline H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernandez, Catherine A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKitzinger, Beatrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKumler, Aden, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLakey, Christopher R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatton, Pamela A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatton, Pamela A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPeers, Glenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPurtle, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo